def parser(log: str) -> dict[str, str]:
    """
    Parse various test output formats and return a mapping:
    { "ClassName#testName": "pass|fail|skip", ... }

    Primary support: concatenated JUnit-style XML (Maven/Gradle/JUnit/TestNG).
    Also includes some light regex-based fallbacks for non-XML lines.
    """
    import re
    import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET

    results: dict[str, str] = {}

    # ---------- Helper: record status with precedence ----------
    # precedence: fail > skip > pass
    def update_status(test_id: str, status: str) -> None:
        current = results.get(test_id)
        if current is None:
            results[test_id] = status
            return
        if current == status:
            return
        # Upgrade precedence if needed
        precedence = {"fail": 2, "skip": 1, "pass": 0}
        if precedence[status] > precedence[current]:
            results[test_id] = status

    # ---------- Step 1: Extract and parse XML test suites ----------
    # JUnit XML files may be concatenated; there may be XML declarations
    # between them. We strip XML declarations and then match <testsuite>...</testsuite>.
    # Note: we deliberately do NOT anchor on start-of-string to be tolerant of noise.
    cleaned_log = re.sub(r"<\?xml[^>]*\?>", "", log)

    suite_pattern = re.compile(
        r"(<testsuite\b.*?</testsuite>)",
        re.DOTALL | re.IGNORECASE,
    )

    for suite_xml in suite_pattern.findall(cleaned_log):
        # Some tools may inject stray bytes or logs; be conservative
        fragment = suite_xml.strip()
        if not fragment.lower().startswith("<testsuite"):
            continue

        try:
            root = ET.fromstring(fragment)
        except ET.ParseError:
            # Skip malformed fragments; we will try textual parsing later
            continue

        # Handle the case where root is either a <testsuite> or some parent
        # that contains multiple <testsuite> nodes.
        suites = []
        if root.tag.lower().endswith("testsuite"):
            suites = [root]
        else:
            suites = list(root.iter("testsuite"))

        for suite in suites:
            for case in suite.iter("testcase"):
                classname = (case.attrib.get("classname") or "").strip()
                name = (case.attrib.get("name") or "").strip()
                if classname and name:
                    test_id = f"{classname}#{name}"
                elif name:
                    test_id = name
                else:
                    # Can't build a useful identifier
                    continue

                # Determine status based on child tags
                status = "pass"
                has_skipped = False
                has_failure = False

                for child in list(case):
                    tag = child.tag.lower()
                    # Handle potential namespace prefixes
                    if tag.endswith("skipped"):
                        has_skipped = True
                    elif tag.endswith("failure") or tag.endswith("error"):
                        has_failure = True

                if has_skipped:
                    status = "skip"
                if has_failure:
                    status = "fail"

                update_status(test_id, status)

    # ---------- Step 2: Fallbacks for common non-XML formats ----------
    # If XML covered everything, this won't hurt; it will only add tests not yet seen,
    # or potentially upgrade pass->fail/skip if both appear.
    lines = log.splitlines()

    # 2a) pytest style: "path::test_name [options] PASSED/FAILED/SKIPPED/ERROR"
    pytest_pattern = re.compile(
        r"^(?P<id>\S+::\S+)\s+(?P<status>PASSED|FAILED|SKIPPED|ERROR)\b",
        re.IGNORECASE,
    )

    # 2b) unittest style: "TestClass.test_method ... ok/FAIL/ERROR"
    unittest_pattern = re.compile(
        r"^(?P<id>[A-Za-z_][\w\.]*\.[A-Za-z_][\w]*)\s+\.\.\.\s+"
        r"(?P<status>ok|FAIL|ERROR|skipped)",
        re.IGNORECASE,
    )

    # 2c) go test style: "--- PASS: TestName" (optionally with (duration))
    gotest_pattern = re.compile(
        r"^---\s+(?P<status>PASS|FAIL|SKIP):\s+(?P<id>\S+)",
        re.IGNORECASE,
    )

    # 2d) Jest style: "✓ test name", "✕ test name", "○ test name"
    jest_pattern = re.compile(
        r"^[\s]*(?P<symbol>[✓✔✕✖×○◌])\s+(?P<id>.+)$"
    )

    for line in lines:
        line = line.strip()

        # pytest
        m = pytest_pattern.match(line)
        if m:
            tid = m.group("id")
            st = m.group("status").upper()
            mapped = "pass" if st == "PASSED" else "skip" if st == "SKIPPED" else "fail"
            update_status(tid, mapped)
            continue

        # unittest
        m = unittest_pattern.match(line)
        if m:
            tid = m.group("id")
            st = m.group("status").lower()
            if st == "ok":
                mapped = "pass"
            elif st == "skipped":
                mapped = "skip"
            else:  # FAIL, ERROR
                mapped = "fail"
            update_status(tid, mapped)
            continue

        # go test
        m = gotest_pattern.match(line)
        if m:
            tid = m.group("id")
            st = m.group("status").upper()
            mapped = "pass" if st == "PASS" else "skip" if st == "SKIP" else "fail"
            update_status(tid, mapped)
            continue

        # Jest
        m = jest_pattern.match(line)
        if m:
            symbol = m.group("symbol")
            tid = m.group("id").strip()
            if symbol in ("✓", "✔"):
                mapped = "pass"
            elif symbol in ("○", "◌"):
                mapped = "skip"
            else:  # ✕, ✖, ×
                mapped = "fail"
            update_status(tid, mapped)
            continue

    return results

def parser(log: str) -> dict[str, str]:
    # Your improved parser implementation
    import re
    from xml.etree import ElementTree as ET

    results: dict[str, str] = {}

    # ----------------------
    # Helpers
    # ----------------------
    def normalize_name(name: str) -> str:
        return name.strip()

    def status_from_xml_testcase(tc) -> str:
        # Default
        status = "pass"

        # Child elements
        if tc.find("failure") is not None or tc.find("error") is not None:
            return "fail"

        if (
            tc.find("skipped") is not None
            or tc.find("ignore") is not None
            or tc.find("ignored") is not None
        ):
            return "skip"

        # Attributes that might encode status
        attr_status = (tc.get("status") or "").lower()
        attr_skipped = (tc.get("skipped") or "").lower()

        if attr_status in {"skipped", "ignore", "ignored"} or attr_skipped == "true":
            return "skip"

        if attr_status in {"failed", "error"}:
            return "fail"

        return status

    def add_result(name: str, status: str):
        name = normalize_name(name)
        if not name:
            return
        # Overwrite allowed; XML results typically added first
        if status not in {"pass", "fail", "skip"}:
            return
        results[name] = status

    # ----------------------
    # 1) XML parsing with synthetic root
    # ----------------------
    cleaned = re.sub(r"<\?xml[^>]*\?>", "", log)
    wrapped = "<root>" + cleaned + "</root>"

    parsed_any_xml = False
    try:
        root = ET.fromstring(wrapped)
        parsed_any_xml = True

        # Iterate over all testcase elements regardless of hierarchy
        for tc in root.iter("testcase"):
            classname = tc.get("classname") or ""
            name = tc.get("name") or ""
            if not classname and not name:
                continue
            full_name = f"{classname}.{name}" if classname else name
            status = status_from_xml_testcase(tc)
            add_result(full_name, status)
    except Exception:
        parsed_any_xml = False

    # ----------------------
    # 2) Fallback: regex-based per-testsuite parsing if synthetic root failed
    # ----------------------
    if not parsed_any_xml:
        xml_blocks = re.findall(r"(<testsuite[\s\S]*?</testsuite>)", log)
        for block in xml_blocks:
            try:
                suite = ET.fromstring(block)
            except Exception:
                continue

            for tc in suite.findall(".//testcase"):
                classname = tc.get("classname") or ""
                name = tc.get("name") or ""
                if not classname and not name:
                    continue
                full_name = f"{classname}.{name}" if classname else name
                status = status_from_xml_testcase(tc)
                add_result(full_name, status)

    # ----------------------
    # 3) Text-based parsing for other frameworks (pytest, unittest, go test, Jest)
    #    Only add entries that don't already exist from XML.
    # ----------------------
    lines = log.splitlines()

    # pytest-like: file::test_name ... STATUS
    pytest_re = re.compile(
        r"^(?P<name>\S+::\S+.*?)\s+"
        r"(?P<status>PASSED|FAILED|SKIPPED|ERROR|XFAIL|XPASS)\b"
    )

    # unittest-like: TestClass.test_method ... ok/FAIL/ERROR/skipped
    unittest_re = re.compile(
        r"^(?P<name>[\w\.]+\.[A-Za-z_]\w*)\s+\.+\s+"
        r"(?P<status>ok|OK|FAIL|ERROR|skipped|SKIPPED)"
    )

    # go test-like: --- PASS|FAIL|SKIP: TestName
    go_re = re.compile(r"^---\s+(PASS|FAIL|SKIP):\s+(?P<name>\S+)")

    # Jest-like symbols
    jest_pass_sym = re.compile(r"^\s*[✓✔]\s+(?P<name>.+)")
    jest_fail_sym = re.compile(r"^\s*[✕✖×]\s+(?P<name>.+)")
    jest_skip_sym = re.compile(r"^\s*[○◌]\s+(?P<name>.+)")

    for line in lines:
        line = line.rstrip("\n")

        # pytest
        m = pytest_re.match(line)
        if m:
            name = normalize_name(m.group("name"))
            if name not in results:
                status_word = m.group("status").upper()
                if status_word in {"PASSED", "XPASS"}:
                    status = "pass"
                elif status_word in {"FAILED", "ERROR"}:
                    status = "fail"
                else:  # SKIPPED, XFAIL
                    status = "skip"
                add_result(name, status)
            continue

        # unittest
        m = unittest_re.match(line)
        if m:
            name = normalize_name(m.group("name"))
            if name not in results:
                status_word = m.group("status").lower()
                if status_word in {"ok"}:
                    status = "pass"
                elif status_word in {"fail", "error"}:
                    status = "fail"
                else:  # skipped
                    status = "skip"
                add_result(name, status)
            continue

        # go test
        m = go_re.match(line)
        if m:
            name = normalize_name(m.group("name"))
            if name not in results:
                kind = m.group(1)
                if kind == "PASS":
                    status = "pass"
                elif kind == "FAIL":
                    status = "fail"
                else:
                    status = "skip"
                add_result(name, status)
            continue

        # Jest symbols
        m = jest_pass_sym.match(line)
        if m:
            name = normalize_name(m.group("name"))
            if name not in results:
                add_result(name, "pass")
            continue

        m = jest_fail_sym.match(line)
        if m:
            name = normalize_name(m.group("name"))
            if name not in results:
                add_result(name, "fail")
            continue

        m = jest_skip_sym.match(line)
        if m:
            name = normalize_name(m.group("name"))
            if name not in results:
                add_result(name, "skip")
            continue

    return results

                # Check attributes like status="SKIPPED" or result="failure"
                status_attr = (attrs.get("status") or attrs.get("result") or "").lower()
                if status_attr in ("skipped", "ignore", "ignored"):
                    status = "skip"
                elif status_attr in ("failure", "failed", "error"):
                    status = "fail"
                else:
                    status = "pass"

            set_status(test_id, status)

    # ------------------------------------------------------------------
    # 2) pytest-style lines: file::test STATUS
    # ------------------------------------------------------------------
    # Example: tests/test_x.py::TestClass::test_thing PASSED
    pytest_re = re.compile(
        r"^(?P<id>\S+::\S+)\s+(?P<status>PASSED|FAILED|SKIPPED|ERROR)\b",
        re.MULTILINE,
    )

    for m in pytest_re.finditer(log):
        test_id = m.group("id")
        s = m.group("status").upper()
        if s == "PASSED":
            set_status(test_id, "pass")
        elif s in ("FAILED", "ERROR"):
            set_status(test_id, "fail")
        elif s == "SKIPPED":
            set_status(test_id, "skip")

    # ------------------------------------------------------------------
    # 3) unittest / nose-style lines
    # ------------------------------------------------------------------
    # Pattern: Class.test_method ... ok / FAIL / ERROR
    unittest_simple_re = re.compile(
        r"^([\w\.]+)\s+\.\.\.\s+(ok|OK|FAIL|ERROR|SKIP|skipped)$",
        re.MULTILINE,
    )

    for m in unittest_simple_re.finditer(log):
        test_id = m.group(1)
        s = m.group(2).lower()
        if s in ("ok",):
            set_status(test_id, "pass")
        elif s in ("fail", "error"):
            set_status(test_id, "fail")
        elif s in ("skip", "skipped"):
            set_status(test_id, "skip")

    # Pattern: test_name (pkg.Class) ... ok / FAIL / ERROR
    unittest_verbose_re = re.compile(
        r"^(\w+)\s+\(([^\)]+)\)\s+\.\.\.\s+(ok|OK|FAIL|ERROR|SKIP|skipped)$",
        re.MULTILINE,
    )

    for m in unittest_verbose_re.finditer(log):
        method = m.group(1)
        cls = m.group(2)
        s = m.group(3).lower()
        test_id = f"{cls}.{method}"
        if s in ("ok",):
            set_status(test_id, "pass")
        elif s in ("fail", "error"):
            set_status(test_id, "fail")
        elif s in ("skip", "skipped"):
            set_status(test_id, "skip")

    # ------------------------------------------------------------------
    # 4) Go test output
    # ------------------------------------------------------------------
    # Pattern: --- PASS: TestName (0.00s)
    go_re = re.compile(
        r"^---\s+(PASS|FAIL|SKIP):\s+([^\s(]+)",
        re.MULTILINE,
    )

    for m in go_re.finditer(log):
        s = m.group(1).upper()
        test_name = m.group(2)
        if s == "PASS":
            set_status(test_name, "pass")
        elif s == "FAIL":
            set_status(test_name, "fail")
        elif s == "SKIP":
            set_status(test_name, "skip")

    # ------------------------------------------------------------------
    # 5) Jest-style symbol lines
    # ------------------------------------------------------------------
    # ✓ test name, ✕ test name, ○ test name
    jest_symbol_re = re.compile(
        r"^[\s]*([✓✕○])\s+(.+)$",
        re.MULTILINE,
    )

    for m in jest_symbol_re.finditer(log):
        symbol = m.group(1)
        name = m.group(2).strip()
        if symbol == "✓":
            set_status(name, "pass")
        elif symbol == "✕":
            set_status(name, "fail")
        elif symbol == "○":
            set_status(name, "skip")

    return results

def parser(log: str) -> dict[str, str]:
    import re
    import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET

    results: dict[str, str] = {}

    # ----------------------------
    # 1) Primary path: parse XML
    # ----------------------------
    #
    # We may have multiple XML documents concatenated, e.g.:
    #   <?xml ...?><testsuite ...>...</testsuite><?xml ...?><testsuite ...>...</testsuite>
    #
    # Strategy:
    #   - Find every <testsuite ...>...</testsuite> block with a DOTALL regex.
    #   - Ignore XML declarations; ET can parse a clean <testsuite>...</testsuite> snippet.
    #   - For each <testcase>, detect status by presence of child tags.
    #
    suite_pattern = re.compile(r"(<testsuite\b[\s\S]*?</testsuite>)", re.IGNORECASE)
    suites = suite_pattern.findall(log)

    def record_test(full_name: str, status: str) -> None:
        # status is one of pass/fail/skip; if already present, prefer "fail" over others,
        # "skip" over "pass" to capture worst status when duplicated.
        prev = results.get(full_name)
        if prev is None:
            results[full_name] = status
        else:
            order = {"pass": 0, "skip": 1, "fail": 2}
            if order[status] > order[prev]:
                results[full_name] = status

    for suite_xml in suites:
        # Strip any leading BOM or whitespace; XML declarations are already outside this snippet
        snippet = suite_xml.strip()
        if not snippet:
            continue
        try:
            root = ET.fromstring(snippet)
        except ET.ParseError:
            # Some logs may be truncated; skip unparseable chunks
            continue

        # Handle standard surefire structure
        for tc in root.findall(".//testcase"):
            classname = tc.get("classname", "") or ""
            name = tc.get("name", "") or ""
            if classname:
                full_name = f"{classname}.{name}"
            else:
                full_name = name

            # Determine status: any <skipped> or <skip> child => skip
            # any <failure> or <error> => fail
            # otherwise => pass
            # (Use .find with full search to be tolerant of nesting)
            status = "pass"
            if tc.find("skipped") is not None or tc.find("skip") is not None:
                status = "skip"
            if tc.find("failure") is not None or tc.find("error") is not None:
                status = "fail"

            record_test(full_name, status)

    # If we already got results from XML, we can return them; they are the most reliable.
    # However, we still may want to support non-XML-only logs, so only early-return
    # when there is at least one parsed test case.
    if results:
        return results

    # ----------------------------------------------------
    # 2) Fallbacks: non-XML test output (JUnit, pytest...)
    # ----------------------------------------------------
    #
    # These are generic patterns that often show up in plain console logs, not XML.
    #
    # 2.a) pytest-style: file.py::test_name  STATUS
    pytest_pattern = re.compile(
        r"^(?P<name>\S+::\S+)\s+(?P<status>PASSED|FAILED|SKIPPED|ERROR)\b",
        re.MULTILINE,
    )
    for m in pytest_pattern.finditer(log):
        name = m.group("name")
        status_word = m.group("status")
        if status_word in ("FAILED", "ERROR"):
            status = "fail"
        elif status_word == "SKIPPED":
            status = "skip"
        else:
            status = "pass"
        record_test(name, status)

    # 2.b) unittest-style: TestClass.test_method ... ok/FAIL/ERROR/skipped
    unittest_pattern = re.compile(
        r"^(?P<name>(?:\w+\.)*\w+\.\w+)\s+\.{3}\s+(?P<status>ok|FAIL|ERROR|skipped)",
        re.MULTILINE,
    )
    for m in unittest_pattern.finditer(log):
        name = m.group("name")
        word = m.group("status")
        if word in ("FAIL", "ERROR"):
            status = "fail"
        elif word == "skipped":
            status = "skip"
        else:
            status = "pass"
        record_test(name, status)

    # 2.c) go test: --- PASS: TestName (0.00s)
    go_pattern = re.compile(
        r"^---\s+(?P<status>PASS|FAIL|SKIP):\s+(?P<name>\S+)",
        re.MULTILINE,
    )
    for m in go_pattern.finditer(log):
        name = m.group("name")
        word = m.group("status")
        if word == "FAIL":
            status = "fail"
        elif word == "SKIP":
            status = "skip"
        else:
            status = "pass"
        record_test(name, status)

    # 2.d) Jest-style: ✓ test name / ✕ test name / ○ test name
    jest_symbol_pattern = re.compile(
        r"^[\s]*([✓✔])\s+(?P<name>.+)$|^[\s]*([✕✖])\s+(?P<name_fail>.+)$|^[\s]*[○]\s+(?P<name_skip>.+)$",
        re.MULTILINE,
    )
    for m in jest_symbol_pattern.finditer(log):
        if m.group(1) is not None:
            name = m.group("name").strip()
            status = "pass"
        elif m.group(3) is not None:
            name = m.group("name_fail").strip()
            status = "fail"
        else:
            name = m.group("name_skip").strip()
            status = "skip"
        record_test(name, status)

    # 2.e) Jest keyword style: "PASS  path" / "FAIL  path"
    jest_word_pattern = re.compile(
        r"^\s*(PASS|FAIL)\s+([^\s].+)$",
        re.MULTILINE,
    )
    for m in jest_word_pattern.finditer(log):
        word, name = m.group(1), m.group(2).strip()
        status = "pass" if word == "PASS" else "fail"
        record_test(name, status)

    return results

    import re
    import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET

    results: dict[str, str] = {}

    # Find all testsuite XML blocks in the noisy log
    for m in re.finditer(r'<testsuite\b[^>]*>.*?</testsuite>', log, re.DOTALL | re.IGNORECASE):
        block = m.group(0)
        try:
            root = ET.fromstring(block)
        except Exception:
            continue

        for tc in root.findall('.//testcase'):
            name = tc.get('name') or ''
            classname = tc.get('classname') or ''
            test_name = f"{classname}.{name}" if classname else name

            status = "pass"
            # Determine status based on child elements
            for child in list(tc):
                # Support possible XML namespaces
                tag = child.tag
                if '}' in tag:
                    tag = tag.split('}', 1)[1]
                tag = tag.lower()
                if tag in ("failure", "error"):
                    status = "fail"
                    break
                elif tag == "skipped":
                    status = "skip"
                    break

            if test_name:
                results[test_name] = status

    return results

def get_pertest_cmd(testcase_list:list[str])->dict[str,str]:
    """
    Map JUnit-style testcase names to Gradle commands that run that single test
    with verbose output.

    Input examples (from the parser):
      "edu.umd.cs.findbugs.AbstractBugReporterTest.verifyRelaxedOperationWorks()"
      "edu.umd.cs.findbugs.ba.Issue1367Test.testIssue(SpotBugsRunner)"
    """
    result: dict[str, str] = {}

    # We assume all these tests live in the :spotbugs-tests module, which is where
    # the SpotBugs JUnit tests are defined and configured to use JUnit Platform.
    module = ":spotbugs-tests"

    for testcase in testcase_list:
        fq = testcase

        # Strip trailing parentheses for Gradle's --tests pattern
        # e.g. "Class.method()" -> "Class.method"
        if fq.endswith(")"):
            # remove the parameter list but keep the method name
            # find the last '(' and cut it (plus closing ')')
            open_paren = fq.rfind("(")
            if open_paren != -1:
                fq_no_paren = fq[:open_paren]
                # also strip a possible trailing ')' if any remained
                if fq_no_paren.endswith(")"):
                    fq_no_paren = fq_no_paren[:-1]
                fq = fq_no_paren

        # Gradle --tests expects "fully.qualified.ClassName.methodName"
        gradle_pattern = fq

        cmd = (
            f"cd /testbed && "
            f"./gradlew {module}:test --no-daemon "
            f'--tests "{gradle_pattern}" '
            f"--info --tests \"{gradle_pattern}\""
        )
        # Note: duplicated --tests is harmless; it's just to emphasize per-test filtering
        result[testcase] = cmd

    return result
